    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it doesnt feel like cognitive bias though. its not just random patterns. it's like i see a visual 'echo' of something that hasn't happened yet, and it has this heavy, specific energy to it. like the mug wasnt just a mug, it was a sign. if its just a coincidence why did it feel so much more real than everything else around me?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That intense sense of realness and specific \"energy\" is very common in what psychologists call hypnagogic or hypnopompic hallucinations, often triggered by high stress or fatigue. While these experiences can feel undeniable, they are frequently the brain's way of creating vivid flash-forwards rather than actual psychic foresight. Engaging a mental health professional can help determine if this is a stress response or something else, ensuring you get support without jumping to fear-based conclusions.",
      "source": "target",
